1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3 h6 9. Bh4 Nbd7 10. O-O-O Qc7 11. Be2 b5 12. Bxf6! { An important move! We take this knight out immediately in order to distract the knight from defending the e5 pawn break } (12. e5?! Bb7 13. Qg3? { The usual queen remaneuver drops an important center pawn. } 13... dxe5 14. fxe5 Qxe5 $17) 12... Nxf6 (12... Bxf6?? 13. e5! dxe5 (13... Bb7 14. Ndxb5!! axb5 15. Nxb5 Qb8 (15... Bxf3?? 16. Nxc7+ Kd8 17. Bxf3 Rxa2 18. Kb1! $18) 16. Qxb7! Qxb7 17. Nxd6+ $18 { [%cal Gd6b7,Gd6e8] }) 14. Ndxb5!! axb5 15. Nxb5 (15. Qxa8 { Also winning, but the main line is more solid. }) 15... Qa5 16. Qxa8 Qxa8 17. Nc7+ Ke7 18. Nxa8 Bb7 19. Bb5 { [%csl Gd7] } 19... Rd8 20. Bxd7 Rxd7 21. Nb6 $18) 13. e5 { The main winning attempt } 13... Bb7 (13... Nd5?? 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. e6 Bxe6 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Qg4 $18 { [%cal Gg4g7,Gg4e6] }) 14. Qg3 { This queen maneuver now successfully defends the center } 14... dxe5 (14... Nd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Qxg7 $16) 15. fxe5 Nd5 (15... Ne4 { A rare sideline, but one that still requires extreme precision: } 16. Nxe6! Qxc3!! 17. Nxg7+ Kf8 18. Ne6+ Ke8 (18... fxe6?? 19. Rhf1+ $18) 19. Qxc3 Nxc3 20. Nc7+ Kf8 21. bxc3 Rc8 22. Nd5 $14 { Black can once again hope to transition to an opposite color bishop endgame here too, but it should be a worse version for black than the mainline. } { Azarov, Sergei - Cernousek, Lukas, 1-0, CZE-chT 0809, 2009, https://lichess.org/Z7EqlZqr }) (15... Nd7?? 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Qg6+ Kd8 18. Qxe6 Re8 19. Qg6 Bg5+ (19... Qxe5?? 20. Qb6+ Kc8 21. Rxd7 Kxd7 22. Bg4+ Qf5 23. Bxf5#) 20. Kb1 $18 { Also should be crushing for white because black's king is exposed in the center. }) 16. Nxe6!! { White has to act quickly or will be over-run on the queenside. } 16... fxe6 17. Qg6+ Kd7 (17... Kf8?? 18. Rhf1+ $18 Kg8 19. Qf7+ Kh7 20. Bd3#) (17... Kd8?? 18. Qxe6 $18 { [%cal Gd1d8] }) 18. Nxd5!? { I am recommending an extremely spicy try for white here. Instead of transitioning into an opposite color bishop (+rook) endgame up a pawn, we can sacrifice an entire rook here and have full compensation. With best play, it's probably still a draw, but white is in the driver seat and black needs to find only moves throughout to avoid immediate death. } (18. Bg4 Qxe5 19. Nxd5 Qg5+ 20. Qxg5 Bxg5+ 21. Kb1 Bxd5 22. Rxd5+ { This endgame is extremely difficult to win because of the opposite color bishops. However, white has the upper hand as this e6 pawn will fall. } { Fleetwood, Daniel M - Stalmach, Kamil, 1-0, MT-Muir/A (USA), 2012, https://lichess.org/rWHDP1gz }) 18... exd5 { Forced. } (18... Bxd5?? 19. Bg4! { And Rxd5 followed by Rd1 will win the queen in basically every line. } 19... Qxe5 (19... Qc6? $18 { Transposes to the Qxe5 line here but black is down an extra pawn. }) 20. Rxd5+ Qxd5 21. Rd1 Bg5+ 22. Kb1 Bd2 23. Bxe6+ Qxe6 24. Rxd2+ Ke7 25. Qxg7+ Ke8 26. Qxh8+ $18) (18... Qxe5?? 19. Nb6+ Kc6 20. Nxa8 Qg5+ 21. Qxg5 Bxg5+ 22. Kb1 Bxa8 23. Bf3+ $18) 19. Bg4+ Kd8 20. Qe6 { The threat is Rxd5+, winning. } 20... Qc6 (20... Bg5+! 21. Kb1 Qe7 22. Qb6+ Qc7 (22... Ke8?? 23. Rhf1 h5 24. Bf5 { [%cal Gf5g6] } 24... Rh6 25. Bg6+ Rxg6 26. Qxg6+ Kd8 27. Rf7 $18 { Or black can lose by force. }) 23. Qe6 Qe7 $10 { Sadly, there is a draw here by force if black finds it... }) 21. Rxd5+! { White sacrifices the rook anyway! } 21... Qxd5 22. Rd1 Bg5+ 23. Kb1 Bd2 (23... Qxd1+ 24. Bxd1 $16 { One try for black. However, with the exposed king, it's pretty clear that white has the winning chances here until black can (if ever) coordinate the rooks and find king safety. }) 24. Qb6+ Ke8 (24... Ke7?? 25. Qc7+ Kf8 26. e6 $18 { And amazingly, black cannot defend the f7 square. }) 25. Bf3! Qxe5 26. Qxb7 { The threat is Bh5+ as well as taking the free rook on a8. Black must tread extremely carefully... } { [%csl Ga8] } 26... Rd8 (26... Rb8?? 27. Bh5+! Qxh5 28. Qxb8+ Ke7 29. Qc7+ Ke6 30. Rxd2 $18) 27. Rf1! { Stopping the king from finding safety! } 27... Rd4 (27... Bf4!? 28. g3 { Moving the bishop anywhere gets mated immediately } 28... Be3?? (28... Kf8 29. gxf4 Qf6 30. Re1 { White can play on here, but with best play black should be able to sacrifice back the exchange and equalize. }) 29. Bc6+! Rd7 30. Qxd7#) 28. Qc8+ Ke7 (28... Rd8?? 29. Bh5+ g6 (29... Qxh5?? 30. Qe6#) 30. Bxg6+ Ke7 31. Rf7+ Kd6 32. Qxa6+ Kd5 33. Qxb5+ Kd6 34. Qb6+ Kd5 35. Qb7+ Kc5 36. Rc7+ Kd6 (36... Kd4 37. Qb6+ Qc5 38. Qxc5#) 37. Qc6#) 29. Qxh8 Rd8 30. Qh7 Bg5 31. Qe4 Qxe4 32. Bxe4 $14 { White is up a pawn but black has real drawing chances here with the opposite color bishops } *


