1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3 h6 9. Bh4 Nbd7 10. O-O-O Qc7 11. Be2 Rb8 12. Qg3! { An important move. We once again stop g5, put pressure on the g7 pawn, and in some lines prepare the thematic e5 break. } 12... O-O (12... Rg8? { The main move here at the pro level is a blunder, and is not played any longer. } 13. Rhf1 (13. Nxe6 { Also completely winning, and equally sharp. } 13... fxe6 14. Qg6+ Kf8 15. Rhf1) 13... g5 14. fxg5 Ne5 (14... hxg5 15. Bxg5 Ne5 16. h4 $16) 15. Nf3 hxg5 16. Bxg5 Nxf3 17. Bxf3 Nd7 18. Bxe7 Rxg3 19. Bxd6 Qxd6 20. Rxd6 Rg8 $18) (12... Kf8? $18 { As long as you don't get greedy looking for a knockout, this is already over. }) (12... b5? 13. Qxg7 Rg8 14. Qxh6 $16) 13. Bf3 { White can calmly build up an attack on the king now that we know where he will reside. Normal attacking moves are sufficient here. } { [%cal Gh1e1,Ge4e5] } 13... Nb6 14. Rhe1 Bd7 (14... Nc4 15. e5 dxe5 16. fxe5 Ne8 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Re4 $16 { [%cal Ge4g4,Gg4h4] }) 15. e5 dxe5 16. fxe5 Nfd5 17. Bxe7 Nxe7 18. Ne4 $16 { Stronger central control, more active pieces, and the knight and rook on the b file are obviously misplaced. } { [%cal Ge4d6] } *


[Event "Winning attempts for white in the Bg5 Sicilian Najdorf: Browne variation 11...O-O"]
