1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 { A rare move, but one that can easily transpose back into the main line } 8. Bh4 Be7 (8... g5? { Too early } 9. fxg5 Nfd7?? 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. Qh5+ Ke7 12. gxh6+ $18 Nf6 13. Bxf6+ Kxf6 14. Qh4+ Kf7 15. Qxd8) 9. Qf3 g5?! { This interesting pawn sacrifice was tried by 3 Argetinian GMs (including Miguel Najdorf himself) simultaneously in the 1955 Interzonal tournament against the Soviet team. All three soviets won. } 10. fxg5 Nfd7 11. Qh5! { The modern approved refutation } (11. Nxe6? fxe6 12. Qh5+ Kf8 13. Bb5 { An infamous line that Fischer himself proved to be equal with this sneaky move: } 13... Rh7! $10) 11... Ne5 (11... Bxg5?? 12. Bxg5 Qxg5 13. Nxe6 Qxh5 14. Ng7+ Ke7 15. Nxh5 $18) 12. Bg3 Bxg5 13. Nf3 Nbd7 (13... Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 Nc6 (14... Qb6 15. h4 Qe3+ 16. Qxe3 Bxe3 17. Bxd6 $16) 15. h4 Bf6 (15... Nd4? 16. Qd3 Bf6 17. O-O-O $16) 16. O-O-O $16) (13... Nbc6?! { Blocking the LSB forever can't be best } 14. Nxg5 Qxg5 15. Be2 b5 16. O-O Bb7 (16... b4 17. Na4 Bb7 18. Rad1 O-O-O 19. Bf4 Qxh5 20. Bxh5 $16 { In this sample line, it's clear white's bishop pair rules the board. }) 17. Rad1 $16) 14. Nxg5 Qxg5 15. Qd1 (15. Be2?! b5 16. O-O b4 17. Na4?! Bb7 $15 { In this variation, the b7 bishop is quite active. }) 15... h5!? (15... b5?! 16. Qxd6 Bb7 $16 { With Qc7 coming next, there are simply too many dark squared weaknesses. }) 16. Be2 h4 17. Bf2 Qxg2 18. Rg1 Qxh2 19. Qd4 { If white can castle queenside and maintain the queens, the attack rages on. } 19... Qf4 20. Be3 Qf6 21. Qxd6 Qe7 22. Qd4 $16 { White will castle queenside next and retain a serious initiative. Practically, this position is great for white, but black has dominant control over the e5 square so it will still take some effort to win. } *


