1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Nc6? 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. e5 { This priyome of exchanging on c6 and playing e5 will occur in many lines where black play Nc6 instead of the typical Nbd7. Here especially, black is already in trouble. } 9... h6 (9... dxe5?! 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. fxe5 h6 12. Bh4 g5 13. O-O-O+ Kc7 14. Bg3 Nd5 15. Ne4 $18 { Positionally winning here too. }) 10. Bh4 g5 11. fxg5 Nd5 12. Ne4 Qb6 (12... dxe5 13. Nf6+! Nxf6 14. Qxd8+ Kxd8 15. gxf6 $16) 13. c3! { By pre-empting any checks, white threatens to play g6! and crash through to the centralized black king. } 13... dxe5!? (13... Qe3+!? 14. Qe2 Qxe2+ 15. Bxe2 dxe5 16. g6 f5 17. Nf6+ Nxf6 18. Bxf6 Rg8 19. O-O-O Be7 (19... Rxg6?? 20. Bh5 $18) 20. Bxe5 $18 { Even without the queens, white's dark squared bishop remains king } { [%cal Gg8g6,Ge2h5] }) (13... Qxb2?? 14. g6 fxg6 15. Rb1 Qxa2 16. Bf2 dxe5 17. Bd3 Be7 18. O-O O-O 19. Ra1 Qb2 20. Qg4 Kg7 21. Rfb1 $18 { Black's queen is trapped and his king remains unsafe. }) (13... hxg5? 14. Bxg5 Be7 15. Bxe7 Kxe7 16. exd6+ Kd7 $16) 14. g6! fxg6 15. Bf2 { Prevents Qe3+ and tempts black into once again taking the poisoned b2 pawn } 15... c5 (15... Qxb2? { Transposing to the previous line } 16. Rb1 Qa3 17. Bc4 Be7 (17... Nxc3?? { The following is one of many ways that this goes badly for black. } 18. Qg4! Nxb1 19. Qxg6+ Kd7 20. O-O { [%csl Gd7] } 20... Nc3 21. Qxe6+ Kc7 22. Qxe5+ Bd6 23. Nxd6 Qxd6 24. Qa5+ Kd7 25. Qxc3 $18) 18. Qg4 { [%cal Gg4g6] } 18... Nf4 19. g3 h5 20. Qf3 Nd5 21. O-O Rf8 22. Qd3 $18) 16. Qg4 Nf4 (16... Qxb2?? 17. Qxg6+ Ke7 18. Rd1 $18 { [%cal Gf2h4] }) 17. O-O-O Be7 18. Be3 Qc6 19. Bd3 h5! (19... Nxd3+?? 20. Rxd3 Rg8 21. Bxc5 Bxc5 22. Nf6+ Kf7 23. Nxg8 Kxg8 24. Qxg6+ Kh8 25. Rd8+ $18) 20. Qf3 Bb7 21. Bxf4 exf4 $16 { Markus, Roland - Wosch, Arkadiusz, 1/2-1/2, FICGS__CHESS__CLASS_M__000070, 2014, https://lichess.org/HehMXlwc } *


