1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Be7 (7... h6 8. Bh4 Be7 9. Qf3 g5 (9... Nbd7 10. O-O-O g5? 11. fxg5 Ne5 12. gxf6! Nxf3 13. fxe7 Qa5 14. Nxf3 $18 { White has three pieces for the queen and a monster passed pawn on e7. Black cannot castle and is completely lost. }) 10. fxg5 { The Argentine gambit: A legit possibility, but one that keeps black on their toes. See the corresponding chapter. }) (7... Nbd7 8. Qf3 h6 9. Bh4 g5? 10. fxg5 Ne5?? 11. Qxf6 $18) 8. Qf3 h6 (8... Qb6 9. O-O-O Nbd7 10. g4 h6 11. Bh4 g5!? 12. fxg5 Ne5 13. Qg3 Nfxg4 14. g6! Bxh4 15. gxf7+ Kxf7 16. Qxh4 $16) 9. Bh4 Qc7 10. O-O-O Nbd7 { Note that g4 here is bad because g5 is finally prepared. Instead, we have transposed to the Browne variation. See the corresponding chapters. } 11. Be2 g5? 12. fxg5 Ne5 13. Qe3 Nfg4 14. Bxg4 Nxg4 15. Qd2 $16 { White is up a pawn with no problems at all. See the chapter titled "Browne variation" for how this plays out. } *


