1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 8. Bh4 Qb6 9. a3 Be7 10. Bf2 Qc7 11. Qf3 Nbd7 12. O-O-O b5 13. g4 Bb7!? { Played slightly more often than g5. } 14. Bg2 Rc8 (14... g5 15. h4 gxf4 16. g5 { This usual reaction to g5 will be explored further in the 13...g5 chapter } 16... Ne5 17. Qxf4 Nfg4 (17... hxg5!? { MVL line: } 18. hxg5 Rxh1 19. Rxh1 Nfd7 20. Kb1 O-O-O $10 { With best play, this should be equal. However, if a black knight is maintained on the e5 outpost forever, then black will be the one who is better. White must attack the vulnerable e5 and f7 (possibly even e6 too) points to maintain any advantage. } { Kruse, Herbert - Bergmann, Michael, 1/2-1/2, FICGS__CHESS__WCH_CANDIDATES_FINAL__000, 2018, https://lichess.org/J1bMHz2K }) 18. g6!! { Now that the knight is tied down to the g4 knight, white can break down the kingside pawn structure with this pawn sack. } 18... Rf8 (18... fxg6 19. Nxe6 $16) 19. Bg3 $14 { If black ever captures on g6, white has the Nxe6 counterattack. }) 15. Kb1 b4 (15... g5 16. Qh3!? { Simply to get out of the Ne5 move with tempo, thereby threatening e5! } (16. h4 { The usual reaction sort of works here too... but black might be able to wriggle out with a draw... } 16... Rg8! { Nogga, Uwe - Rook, Detlef, 1/2-1/2, GER/GM03 (GER), 2014, https://lichess.org/9tyMycSt } (16... gxf4?! 17. g5 Ne5 18. Qxf4 { Dubovik, Viktor - Korshunov, Sergey, 1/2-1/2, UKR/C32/FL1 (UKR), 2019, https://lichess.org/1IzgboFm })) 16... Nh7 (16... Nc5? { Nakamura, Hi - Vachier Lagrave, Maxime, 1-0, 8th London Classic 2016, https://lichess.org/2hDAhgsB }) 17. e5! Bxg2 18. Qxg2 gxf4 19. exd6 Bxd6 20. Rhe1 $14) 16. axb4 d5 (16... a5 17. b5 a4 18. h4 $16) 17. e5 Ne4 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. Qe2 Bxb4 20. f5 Nc5 (20... Qxe5?? 21. fxe6 fxe6 22. Bg3 Qf6 23. Rhf1 Qe7 24. Bxe4 $18) (20... Nxe5 21. fxe6 O-O 22. Bxe4 $16 { At least black has castled, but the attack on the kingside is obviously faster than the attack on the queenside }) 21. g5! { Just like black's earlier b4 move, this is purely with the idea of sacrificing pawns to open up files at all costs: } 21... hxg5 22. h4 g4!? (22... Bc3!? 23. fxe6 Bxb2 24. exf7+ Qxf7 25. hxg5 Rxh1 26. Rxh1 Bxd4 27. Bxd4 $16 { White keeps the bishop pair, a slightly safer king, and better piece coordination in this bizarre position. White should be the only one pushing for a win. }) (22... gxh4?? 23. Bxh4 $18 { Threatening Bd8!! Black is dead with his king stuck in the center here. }) 23. h5 Na4 24. h6! gxh6 25. fxe6 Nxb2! 26. exf7+ Qxf7 27. e6 Qg7 28. Nf5 Qf6 29. Bxe4 Na4 30. Bd4! Qxd4! 31. Rxd4 Nc3+ 32. Kb2 Nxe2 33. Rxb4 Bxe4 34. Rxe4 Rb8+ 35. Ka1 $18 { Hilariously, the knight is trapped. The only attempt to save the knight fails spectacularly: } 35... Nc3 36. Rxg4 Nd5 (36... Rf8 37. e7 Rxf5 38. Rg8+ Kxe7 39. Rxb8 $18) 37. Rg7 { Nd6+ is a mate threat, so black has to shed material in order to avoid getting mated } 37... Rb6 38. Ra7 $18 { [%csl Gh8][%cal Ga7a8,Ga8h8] } *


