1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 8. Bh4 Qb6 9. a3 Be7 10. Bf2 Qc7 11. Qf3 Nbd7 12. O-O-O b5 13. g4 g5!? { Here the thematic pawn sacrifice once again rears its head. However, in this case, the slight lead in development afforded to white compared to the 3-piece mainline of the Najdorf means that white should be able to get away with a big attack. } 14. h4! { We want to play g5 at all costs, even if black stops it temporarily. } 14... gxf4 15. Be2 { Finishing development and avoiding any later issues with the knights taking out g4. } 15... Ne5 (15... Bb7? 16. g5 { If black is too slow, white immediately crashes through: } 16... Ne5 17. Qxf4 hxg5 18. hxg5 Rxh1 19. Rxh1 Ng6 20. Qe3 Nd7 $16) (15... b4? 16. axb4 Ne5 17. Qxf4 { Caruana, F. - Nakamura, Hi, 1-0, 8th London Classic 2016, https://lichess.org/bKoqC7cy } { Similar to the main line below }) (15... Rg8? 16. g5! hxg5 17. hxg5 Ne5 18. Qxf4 Nfd7 19. Kb1 { A more sensible alternative... } (19. Nxe6 { Cvak, Rudolf - Salzmann, Stefan, 1-0, EU/C2016/pr.18, https://lichess.org/dWqfME7M }) 19... Bxg5 20. Qg3 $18 { Rh5 is coming and the black pieces cannot maintain their current outposts. }) 16. Qxf4 Nexg4 (16... b4 17. axb4 { Transposes to the 2016 Caruana game above. }) 17. Bxg4 e5 { The point of black's play. Black regains the piece and then some if white doesn't act immediately. } 18. Qxf6!! { But white can have none of it with this unbelievable queen sacrifice! } 18... Bxf6 19. Nd5 Qd8 20. Nf5 h5! { Black should give back the queen instead of trying to hold onto bad material. } (20... Bxf5 21. Bxf5 $16 { White sacrifices the queen for two pieces, but has amazing compensation in the form of the d5 and f5 squares, total control of the light squares, and black's terrible bishop on f6 is more of a liability than a strength. } 21... Rb8 22. Rd3) (20... Rb8? 21. Nxf6+ Qxf6 22. Nxd6+ Ke7 23. Bc5 Qf4+ 24. Kb1 Qxg4 25. Nxc8+ Ke8 26. Nd6+ Kd7 27. Nxf7+ Kc7 28. Bd6+ Kb7 29. Bxb8 Rxb8 30. Rhg1 $18) 21. Nxf6+!? { White can insist on playing down a queen though! } (21. Bb6!? { A safer but not as exciting alternative. White retains a small edge in the endgame. } 21... hxg4 22. Bxd8 Bxd8 23. Nxd6+ Kf8 24. Nxc8 Rxc8 25. Ne3 $16 { White returns to f5 in order to defend the h4 pawn. With a good knight against a bad bishop, white should be able to play on. } 25... Rg8 (25... Bxh4 26. Kb1 Bf6 27. Rxh8+ Bxh8 28. Nxg4) 26. Nf5) 21... Qxf6 22. Rxd6 Be6 23. Bh3 Rh6! (23... Rc8 24. Rg1 $16 { White has a total grip on the position. Black attempts to untangle fall short: } 24... Kf8 (24... Rc4 25. Be3 Rxe4 26. Bg5 { [%cal Gg5d8,Gd6d8] }) 25. Be3 Rg8 26. Bg5 Rxg5 27. Rxg5) 24. Rhd1 Kf8! (24... Rg6? 25. Bc5) 25. Bc5 Kg8 26. Rg1+ Kh7 27. Rg5 Rd8 28. Rxa6 Rd7 { Stopping Be7. With complete precision, it's possible black can escape the bind. But white remains in control the entire time and can choose to create a passed pawn with b3-a4 ideas. The queen remains dead, even if it reaches d8. } 29. b3 Qd8 30. Kb2 $14 *


