1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Qb6 8. Qd3 Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. f5 Be7 (10... Qa5!? 11. Bxf6 (11. Be2?! { By doing the typical moves, trying to transpose to the main line, black has the extra option of e5 under good circumstances. } 11... Be7 12. Bd2? (12. O-O?! O-O 13. Bd2 Qc7 14. fxe6 fxe6 $15 { A bad line for white: we want instead to have played g4 instead of castling. }) 12... e5! 13. Nd5 Qd8 $17) 11... gxf6 12. fxe6 fxe6 13. Qc4 Qc5? (13... Kd8 14. Rb3! { Defending the knight means that Qc5 can still be met with Nxe6! } 14... Qe5 15. Be2 { Mkrtchian, Lilit - Romanko, Marina, 1-0, EU-ch (Women) 10th, 2009, https://lichess.org/wydQR191 }) 14. Nxe6) 11. fxe6 fxe6 12. Be2 Qa5 (12... Nc6? { Transposing to a bad line: see the next chapter }) (12... O-O?! 13. Nd5 Qxd3 14. Nxe7+ Kf7 15. cxd3 Kxe7 16. O-O $16 { We saw the same idea in the previous chapter as well. }) (12... Qc5 13. Be3 Qc7 14. O-O O-O 15. Qc4! $14 { Essentially winning the e pawn unless black goes through some contortions. } { [%cal Gc4g8] }) 13. Bd2 { [%cal Gc3d5] } 13... Qc7! { The most precise way to play. By avoiding Nc6, black doesn't give white a chance to claim the open b file and ruin black's structure. Moreover, by repositioning the queen ASAP, black is now finally ready to castle. White has to create problems immediately: g5! } 14. g4 { [%cal Gg4g5] } 14... h6 15. Qh3! { [%cal Gg4g5] } (15. Rg1!? Bd7 16. g5 hxg5 17. Rxg5 { Caruana, F. - Nakamura, Hi, 1-0, 5th Norway Chess 2017, https://lichess.org/3lNsMCJI } 17... Rh7 $10) 15... O-O! { Black can and should grab the bull by the horns here to come out alright. } (15... e5?! 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17. gxf5 Nbd7 18. O-O $14 { Black's king has no shelter on either side of the board now due to the open g and b files. }) (15... g5? 16. Rf1! { White now threatens Bg5 under better circumstances, and continues the attack against the unsafe black king. For instance: } (16. Bxg5?? Qc5! { [%cal Gc5g5,Gc5d4,Gc5c3] }) 16... Qc5 17. e5! Qxe5 18. Nf3 Qc5 19. Na4 Qa7 20. Nxg5 $18) 16. g5 hxg5 17. Nxe6 Qc6 (17... Bxe6?? 18. Qxe6+ Kh8 19. Nd5 Nxd5 20. exd5 Rf6 21. Qe4 $18 { This is just one sample line, but if white gains control of the weakened light squares near black's king, black will simply be mated. } { [%cal Ge2d3,Ge4h7] }) 18. Rf1 { White is threatening Qf5, to play Nd5, so black needs to act immediately: } 18... Nxe4 (18... g4!? 19. Bxg4 Nxg4 20. Rxf8+ Bxf8 21. Qxg4 Qd7 22. Nd5! Qxe6 23. Qxe6+ Bxe6 24. Nc7 Ra7 25. Nxe6 b5 26. Nxf8 Kxf8 27. Bf4 $14 { White can hope to press in this endgame with the active bishop against the passive knight. }) 19. Rxf8+ Bxf8 20. Rb6! (20. Qd3!? { An interesting alternative for white, but this endgame should be drawn with best play too: } 20... Bxe6 (20... Nc5 { Krauß, Heiko - Zill, Eberhard, 1-0, GER/SC76p08 (GER), 2016, https://lichess.org/rwpTCclo }) 21. Nxe4 Qd5 22. Nxg5 Qxd3 23. Bxd3 Bxa2 24. Rxb7 Nc6 $10) 20... Qe8! (20... Qxb6?? 21. Nxe4 $18 { And the white queen cannot be prevented from infiltrating on the weakened light squares. } { [%cal Gh3f5,Gh3e6,Gh3h5] }) (20... Qd7?? 21. Bc4 $18 { [%cal Gc4g8] }) 21. Nxe4 (21. Bc4?? { The move we want to play fails spectacularly... } 21... Nc5 $19 { [%cal Ge8e1] }) 21... Bxe6 22. Qd3 { Black is able to barely keep their light squares together, and so should have an equal position with best play as in: } { Traut, Thomas - Schuller, Jean-Claude, 1/2-1/2, S-Open/4-sf06, 2012, https://lichess.org/880OTuwX } 22... Be7 23. Nxg5 Bxg5 24. Bxg5 Nd7 25. Rxd6 Rc8 $10 { At least white has the bishop pair, but the lack of pawn shelter around their king ensures this game is probably drawn if black keeps the queens on the board. } *


